<!--
# Asset & Incident Management App

 Overview
A microservices-based IT Asset and Incident Management system
built with React, Node.js, Redis, Docker and Kubernetes.

 Architecture
Browser → Nginx → asset-service → redis-asset
                → incident-service → redis-incident


-> **Frontend** - is a React app served via Nginx (on port 80)
-> **Asset-service** - it is a service for managing IT assets (port 5001 # defined in server.js of asset service)
-> **Incident-service** - manages incidents happening with assets. (port 5002 # defined in server.js of incidnet service)
-> **redis-asset** - dedicated redis DB for asset service (redis listens on port 6379)
-> **redis-incident** - dedicated redis DB for incident service (redis listens on port 6379)

## Folder Structure
|-- asset-service/  - Node.js asset microservice  
|-- incident-service/ - Node.js incident microservice
|-- frontend/ -         React front served via Nginx
|-- docker-compose.yaml - Local docker setup to test application locally
|-- k8s/helm -            Application deployement via HELM Kubernetes


# How to run this application locally 
git clone <repo url>
cd microservices
docker compose build 
odocker compose up -d 
Open http://localhost

# How to deploy on kubernetes
cd k8s/helm
helm install asset-incident ./asset-incident-app

## API endpoints (Asset-service)
POST - /api/asset        - create an asset
GET - /api/data          - getl all asset with incidents
PUT - /api/asset/:id     - update asset
DELETE - /api/asset/:id  - delete asset

## Incident service
POST   /api/incident                        - create incident
PUT    /api/incident/:assetId/:incidentId   - update incident
DELETE /api/incident/:assetId/:incidentId   - delete incident


## Environment variables

| Variable             |  Service         |   Docker Value               |    Kubernetes Value           |           Description                                  
|----------------------|------------------|----------------------------- |-----------------------------  |--------------------------------------|
| REDIS_HOST           | asset-service    | redis-asset-db               |    redis-asset-service        | Redis hostname for asset service     |
| REDIS_PORT           | asset-service    | 6379                         |        6379                   | Redis port                           |
| INCIDENT_SERVICE_URL | asset-service    | http://incident-service:5002 | http://incident-service:5002  | URL to call incident service         |   
| REDIS_HOST           | incident-service | redis-incident-db            | redis-incident-service        | Redis hostname for incident service  |
| REDIS_PORT           | incident-service | 6379                         |        6379                   | Redis port                           |



## CI/CD Pipeline
1. Developer pushes code to GitHub or any Source code repository
2. AWS CodePipeline triggers AWS CodeBuild
3. Docker image built and pushed to AWS ECR
4. K8s manifest updated with new image tag with CODE BUILD build number
5. ArgoCD detects change in the source code repo and deploys the changes to Kubernetes




-->
